Bug.WithStack:
The MSLEventBroker::fireEvents(MListener) method permanently removes listeners when uncaught exceptions occur, in the following snippet:
try {
listener.onEvent(eventsToSend);
} catch (Exception e) {
// this is a bad listener so remove it so the next // listeners can get their events. removeListener(listener);
Log.error(MSLPlugin.getDefault(), 1, "removed failed event handler", e); //$NON-NLS-1$
Trace.catching(MSLPlugin.getDefault(), MSLDebugOptions.EXCEPTIONS_CATCHING, getClass(), "fireEvents", e); //$NON-NLS-1$ }
This renders applications (such as mine) unusable, as we have listeners that are responsible for updating the UI, and they disappear. The user's only remedy in these cases is to shut down the workbench and try again.
I understand that uncaught run-time exceptions indicate programming errors, but sometimes these come from code that my code depends on, and can be hard to defend against. I would rather see the workspace log fill up with uncaught exceptions than get a toasted app. Created attachment 27822 patch for fix Created attachment 27823 patch for fix Committed the patch resolving [GMF Restructure] Bug 319140 : product GMF and component Runtime Common was the original product and component for this bug

