Bug.WithStack:
3.2 i200509210010

On the display view, if the current object is an instance of a derived class,
auto-completion does not work when referring to private features
(attributes/methods) when the current context frame corresponds to a method
defined in the same class.

In other words, the following classes:

class A {
  private int counter;
  public void inc() {
    counter++;  // << breakpoint goes here
  }
}

class B extends A {

}

// main class
public class C {
  public static void main(String args[]) {
    B b = new B();
    b.inc();
  }
}

One can type "this.counter" (or only counter) and evaluation works fine, but
auto-completion (for instance, type "this." + Ctrl-Space) does not show the
attribute.
Yes, this is a known limitation currently. Not sure if we can work around this 
as the completions are generated from the Java model's IType. It likely uses 
the "usual" visibility rules.
You can see the completions by unchecking the "Java > Editor > Content Assist" 
preference to "Hide proposals not visible in the current invocation context" 
to off. However, this is a global setting. Ideally the debugger would be able 
to override this when invoking content assist.
Deferred
As of now 'LATER' and 'REMIND' resolutions are no longer supported.
Please reopen this bug if it is still valid for you.

